(571, 1, 3, 1, 'An approved change was implemented to manage a risk. Three months later, the project manager finds that the change did not yield the desired result. In fact, the change led to adverse consequences.\n  \n What should the project manager do to avoid this issue in the future?', 1, 1, 'Complex', 'Project work should be continuously monitored for new, changing, and outdated individual project risks and for changes in the level of overall project risk by applying the Monitor Risks process. The Monitor Risks process uses performance information generated during project execution to determine if the response was effective.\n \n PMBOK Guide Sixth Edition (2018) PMI/PMI/11.7/453', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(572, 3, 12, 1, 'An approved change was implemented to manage a risk. Three months later, the project manager finds that the change did not yield the desired result. In fact, the change led to adverse consequences.\n  \n What should the project manager do to avoid this issue in the future?', 1, 1, 'Complex', 'Project work should be continuously monitored for new, changing, and outdated individual project risks and for changes in the level of overall project risk by applying the Monitor Risks process. The Monitor Risks process uses performance information generated during project execution to determine if the response was effective.\n \n PMBOK Guide Sixth Edition (2018) PMI/PMI/11.7/453', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(573, 1, 3, 1, 'A project manager overhears a conversation in a cafeteria. The speaker says that a possible union action will occur within the next two weeks.\n  \n The project manager knows that any union action will affect the project team, and at this stage of the project, any project delays will cause substantial harm to both budget and schedule. Earlier, the probability of a union action was considered minimal. Thus, it was unanticipated.\n  \n What should the project manager do?', 1, 1, 'High Complex', 'The project manager needs to proactively approach this. By updating the risk register and by communicating this development to the appropriate stakeholders, they will be achieving this.\n  \n PMBOK Guide Sixth Edition (2018) PMI/PMI/11.2.3.1/417', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(574, 3, 12, 1, 'A project manager overhears a conversation in a cafeteria. The speaker says that a possible union action will occur within the next two weeks.\n  \n The project manager knows that any union action will affect the project team, and at this stage of the project, any project delays will cause substantial harm to both budget and schedule. Earlier, the probability of a union action was considered minimal. Thus, it was unanticipated.\n  \n What should the project manager do?', 1, 1, 'High Complex', 'The project manager needs to proactively approach this. By updating the risk register and by communicating this development to the appropriate stakeholders, they will be achieving this.\n  \n PMBOK Guide Sixth Edition (2018) PMI/PMI/11.2.3.1/417', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(575, 1, 3, 1, 'While reviewing the issues log, the project manager notices that tasks assigned to two team members are quite a bit behind schedule.\n  \n What should be done?', 1, 1, 'High Complex', 'The project manager needs to be proactive and review the activities with the team and to identify resolution strategies.\n \n PMBOK Guide Sixth Edition (2018) PMI/PMI/3.4.4.2/61', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(576, 2, 6, 1, 'While reviewing the issues log, the project manager notices that tasks assigned to two team members are quite a bit behind schedule.\n  \n What should be done?', 1, 1, 'High Complex', 'The project manager needs to be proactive and review the activities with the team and to identify resolution strategies.\n \n PMBOK Guide Sixth Edition (2018) PMI/PMI/3.4.4.2/61', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(577, 3, 12, 1, 'While reviewing the issues log, the project manager notices that tasks assigned to two team members are quite a bit behind schedule.\n  \n What should be done?', 1, 1, 'High Complex', 'The project manager needs to be proactive and review the activities with the team and to identify resolution strategies.\n \n PMBOK Guide Sixth Edition (2018) PMI/PMI/3.4.4.2/61', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(578, 1, 3, 1, 'A project sponsor is risk averse and is therefore concerned about negative impacts on the project. To help with this concern, the project team identifies four project risks and then evaluates both the probability of occurrence and the impact of the risk if it occurs. The team uses a 1-5 scale, 1 being the lowest and 5 being the highest. \n \n  Risk Probabilit Impact \n  A 2 3\n  B 2 5\n  C 3 4\n  D 4 4\n \n Based on the table, in what order should the project manager rank these risks for risk management purposes?', 1, 1, 'Complex', 'C\n Probability * Impact provides the risk ranking from highest to lowest. \n A = 2*3 = 6\n B = 2*5 = 10 \n C = 3*4 = 12\n D = 4*4 = 16\n \n Therefore the risks should be ranked in the following order: D, C, B, A\n \n PMBOK Guide Sixth Edition (2018) PMI/PMI/11.4/428', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(579, 3, 12, 1, 'A project sponsor is risk averse and is therefore concerned about negative impacts on the project. To help with this concern, the project team identifies four project risks and then evaluates both the probability of occurrence and the impact of the risk if it occurs. The team uses a 1-5 scale, 1 being the lowest and 5 being the highest. \n \n  Risk Probabilit Impact \n  A 2 3\n  B 2 5\n  C 3 4\n  D 4 4\n \n Based on the table, in what order should the project manager rank these risks for risk management purposes?', 1, 1, 'Complex', 'C\n Probability * Impact provides the risk ranking from highest to lowest. \n A = 2*3 = 6\n B = 2*5 = 10 \n C = 3*4 = 12\n D = 4*4 = 16\n \n Therefore the risks should be ranked in the following order: D, C, B, A\n \n PMBOK Guide Sixth Edition (2018) PMI/PMI/11.4/428', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(580, 1, 2, 1, 'A project manager has put together a project team. During initial meetings, the project manager observes that team members are getting to know each other, feeling excited and positive about the project, and have not been told the specific details of the project.\n  \n In what phase of development is the team?', 1, 1, 'Simple', 'The Forming phase is where the team members meet and learn about the project and their formal roles and responsibilities. Team members tend to be independent and not as open in this phase. \n \n PMBOK Guide Sixth Edition (2018) PMI/PMI/9.4/338', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(581, 2, 5, 1, 'A project manager has put together a project team. During initial meetings, the project manager observes that team members are getting to know each other, feeling excited and positive about the project, and have not been told the specific details of the project.\n  \n In what phase of development is the team?', 1, 1, 'Simple', 'The Forming phase is where the team members meet and learn about the project and their formal roles and responsibilities. Team members tend to be independent and not as open in this phase. \n \n PMBOK Guide Sixth Edition (2018) PMI/PMI/9.4/338', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(582, 3, 12, 1, 'A project manager has put together a project team. During initial meetings, the project manager observes that team members are getting to know each other, feeling excited and positive about the project, and have not been told the specific details of the project.\n  \n In what phase of development is the team?', 1, 1, 'Simple', 'The Forming phase is where the team members meet and learn about the project and their formal roles and responsibilities. Team members tend to be independent and not as open in this phase. \n \n PMBOK Guide Sixth Edition (2018) PMI/PMI/9.4/338', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(583, 1, 3, 1, 'The procurement statement of work (SOW) is completed on a project. However, the customer is not happy because she wants additional work to be completed.\n \n what should the PM do first?', 1, 1, NULL, 'As all the work outlined in the SOW is completed, raising a CR is not an option. A new SOW outlining the additional work has to be drafted and signed off', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(584, 1, 3, 1, 'What is the correct order of performing the processes?', 1, 1, NULL, 'Scope is validated only after QC. Project or the phase is closed after scope is validated. (Project cannot be closed without scope validation', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(585, 2, 6, 1, 'What is the correct order of performing the processes?', 1, 1, NULL, 'Scope is validated only after QC. Project or the phase is closed after scope is validated. (Project cannot be closed without scope validation', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(586, 1, 3, 1, 'The Sprint goal cannot deliver the intended business value because of the extreme change in business priorities. \n \n Who can terminate the Sprint (Iteration)?', 1, 1, NULL, 'Product Owner is authorized to terminate the Sprint if it is determined that a drastic change in direction is required', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(587, 2, 6, 1, 'The Sprint goal cannot deliver the intended business value because of the extreme change in business priorities. \n \n Who can terminate the Sprint (Iteration)?', 1, 1, NULL, 'Product Owner is authorized to terminate the Sprint if it is determined that a drastic change in direction is required', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(588, 1, 3, 1, 'You are a Project Manager for Xansa Consulting. Your latest project includes the upgrade of an organization\'s operating system on 215 servers. You are doing this project under contract. You are in the Contract Closure Process & have reviewed the contracting process to identify lessons learned. What is the name of the tool and technique that you will use to perform the above function?', 1, 1, NULL, '\"Project under contract\" is the key sentence. Contracting processes are reviewed lessons learned are documented during Procurement Audits', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(589, 1, 3, 1, 'You are a Project Manager for XtraMind Consulting. Your current project involves the upgrade of an organization\'s operating system on 220 servers. You are doing this project under contract. You are in the penultimate sprint & closing the contract & know that you should document which of the following?', 1, 1, NULL, 'The project is being delivered under contract (contract type is immaterial). You cannot close the contract without the \"Formal Acceptance\"', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(590, 1, 3, 1, 'You are working on a construction project. Everyone in your team and your senior manager feel that the work is complete except one of your stakeholders who disagrees, and feels that one deliverable is not acceptable. What is the BEST way to handle this conflict?', 1, 1, NULL, 'Key is looking for the BEST solution. All stakeholders are bound by the terms of the contract, hence it has to be consulted & followed in letter & spirit.', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(591, 1, 3, 1, 'You are managing a project to build a new wing in a local school over a summer break. One day, the school & your construction site are destroyed by an earthquake. Your client stresses that you continue work despite the disaster, but you consult the contract and find a clause that states that you are not responsible for any more work. This is referred to as:', 1, 1, NULL, 'Force Majeure clause covers earth quakes, flash floods, landslides, etc.', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(592, 1, 3, 1, 'You have just finished the project for a client to implement a business software solution. All deliverables have been handed over & are already, in use by the client. However, there is still a minor payment to be made by the client on contract closure. You believe that it is now high time to finally close the contract with the client & then, close the project. You approached the client this morning and found that they are somewhat reluctant to close the contract. But you do not exactly understand the reason. What should you NOT do?', 1, 1, NULL, 'NOT do is the key. You cannot leave the stakeholder alone & expect things to get normal. This is never going to happen', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(593, 1, 3, 1, 'You are currently working on an e-commerce project to develop a new user interface for a legacy mainframe banking application. You are under a Time & Material contract to develop an e-commerce based interface for this application. You had a release plan of 10 sprints, but delivered all the user stories in 8 sprints. This means that the profit of your company will decrease. What should you do?', 1, 1, NULL, 'As a certified professional you are expected to be exhibit integrity & transparency over profits. Hence inform the customer & mark the project as complete', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(594, 1, 3, 1, 'The seller delivers a fixed price plus incentive fee project at a cost of $90,000. The terms of the contract are a ceiling price of $120,000, a target cost of $100,000, a target profit of $10,000, and a target price of $110,000. The share ratio is 70/30. The final price (your total reimbursement) is:', 1, 1, NULL, 'Target Cost = $100,000\n Ceiling = $120,000\n BSR=0.3\n Final Fee=((Target cost-Actual Cost) * Seller ratio) + Target Fee = ($100,000-$90,000)0.3 + $10,000 = $13,000.\n Final price = Cost + Final Fee = $90,000+$13,000 = $103000', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(595, 1, 3, 1, 'A contract has just been signed with a construction company to complete a renovation project within 4 months. Due to \"force majeure\", the project will be delayed by an additional 3 months. The construction company has asked for an early termination of the contract. What is the MOST appropriate thing to do in above situation?', 1, 1, NULL, 'As the Force Majeure clause is invoked (considered part of contract terms), the contract has to be closed as per the terms', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(596, 1, 3, 1, 'During project closure a project sponsor complains that the project did not enhance the department\'s knowledge of Android programming and therefore, the project is not complete. The customer has accepted the project. The project manager confirms that all stated objectives and deliverables have been met. He does not find evidence that Android programming knowledge enhancement was an objective for the project. A review of project correspondence shows no mention of the deliverable. The project manager should:-', 1, 1, NULL, 'As \"Android programming knowledge enhancement\" was not captured as deliverable or a stakeholder requirement, you are not contractually bound to deliver it. Proceed with project closure', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(597, 1, 3, 1, 'A project manager for a large international bank has a project team that just executed an electronic funds project involving 4 large vendors. The project manager struggled through every phase of the procurement process since the bank had a pathetic internal contracts department. What would be the MOST appropriate thing to do to ensure the problems are resolved for future projects?', 1, 1, NULL, 'Procurement audits will unearth the reasons behind procurement process delays & lessons learned are documented for further use', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(598, 1, 3, 1, 'You are a project manager at a Construction company that develops and manages residential, retail and commercial properties in Dubai. As the company continues to grow, the company\'s IT infrastructure is unable to meet business needs of the organization. Specifically, you have been assigned to upgrade the company\'s IT infrastructure. Your team has been asked to implement a corporate general ledger system, improve accounting and real estate processes, develop & implement lease tracking system & implement HR & payroll systems. You are also required to perform diagnostics and monthly closures. You are closing out a minor contract on the project phase when you discover that a deliverable has not been received. Your manager wants the problem resolved as soon as possible without much trouble. What should you do?', 1, 1, NULL, 'AS your Manager has requested you to resolve the issuer asap & you cannot close the contract or the project without the missing deliverable, best option is to get the missing deliverable completed', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(599, 1, 3, 1, 'You are about to complete all work associated with a new, systems integration project when the seller comes to you with detailed procedures for closure of the contract. The contract you had signed earlier included different closure procedures. The seller is insisting to use the revised procedures for contract closure. What should you do?', 1, 1, NULL, 'All changes after baselining has to be approved by the CCB. Here the seller is proposing changes after contract signature (contract terms were baselined on contract signature)', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(600, 1, 3, 1, 'While you are working on the project closeout documents, you begin to review the project deliverables & develop checklist of project requirements. You can usually find the requirements for formal contract closeout in the:', 1, 1, NULL, 'Project / work requirements are part of Contract terms & conditions', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(601, 1, 2, 1, 'Jonnie is working as a Project Manager in a Ford Corp Ltd which is in the process of designing a new two-wheeler. He is managing a big team and hence needs to handle number of conflicts. Which of the following is the most ineffective way of conflict resolution?', 1, 1, NULL, 'Out of all the conflict resolution techniques, Forcing creates Win-Lose situation. \n PMs should strive to create Win-Win solution as far as possible', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(602, 2, 5, 1, 'Jonnie is working as a Project Manager in a Ford Corp Ltd which is in the process of designing a new two-wheeler. He is managing a big team and hence needs to handle number of conflicts. Which of the following is the most ineffective way of conflict resolution?', 1, 1, NULL, 'Out of all the conflict resolution techniques, Forcing creates Win-Lose situation. \n PMs should strive to create Win-Win solution as far as possible', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(603, 1, 2, 1, 'Ramie is working as a Project Manager in a Four-Wheeler CORP LTD located in Japan. He finds a conflict between two of his team members. He is not able to confront the problem. What is the next best conflict resolution technique from the following?', 1, 1, NULL, 'As the PM is unable to confront the conflicting problem, Compromising is the next best option.\n Forcing & Withdrawal are not good options as they bring create Win-Lose & Lose-Lose solutions', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(604, 2, 5, 1, 'Ramie is working as a Project Manager in a Four-Wheeler CORP LTD located in Japan. He finds a conflict between two of his team members. He is not able to confront the problem. What is the next best conflict resolution technique from the following?', 1, 1, NULL, 'As the PM is unable to confront the conflicting problem, Compromising is the next best option.\n Forcing & Withdrawal are not good options as they bring create Win-Lose & Lose-Lose solutions', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(605, 1, 2, 1, 'Philip is working as a Scrum Master for AUTOCARS PVT LTD. He is managing a 20 Scrum member team. For conflict resolution he always try to use confronting first. Confronting conflict resolution method is also known as:', 1, 1, NULL, 'Most effective way to resolve a conflict is to confront the problem head-on & trying to get a solution. This creates a Win-Win solution known as Problem-Solving', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(606, 2, 5, 1, 'Philip is working as a Scrum Master for AUTOCARS PVT LTD. He is managing a 20 Scrum member team. For conflict resolution he always try to use confronting first. Confronting conflict resolution method is also known as:', 1, 1, NULL, 'Most effective way to resolve a conflict is to confront the problem head-on & trying to get a solution. This creates a Win-Win solution known as Problem-Solving', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(607, 1, 2, 1, 'Two team members of your Scrum team Philip and Ramie was having a conflict. In one of the Sprints, you used problem solving conflict resolution technique. Problem Solving is :', 1, 1, NULL, 'Problem-solving always leads to creating a Win-Win situation as the conflicting problem (bone of contention) is confronted & a resolution is arrived at', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(608, 2, 5, 1, 'Two team members of your Scrum team Philip and Ramie was having a conflict. In one of the Sprints, you used problem solving conflict resolution technique. Problem Solving is :', 1, 1, NULL, 'Problem-solving always leads to creating a Win-Win situation as the conflicting problem (bone of contention) is confronted & a resolution is arrived at', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(609, 1, 2, 1, 'Two team members of your Scrum team Philip and Ramie were having a conflict. You used Compromising conflict resolution technique. Compromising is :', 1, 1, NULL, 'You did not confront the conflicting problem, but tried to create a Lose-Lose situation by compromising among the conflicting parties', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(610, 2, 5, 1, 'Two team members of your Scrum team Philip and Ramie were having a conflict. You used Compromising conflict resolution technique. Compromising is :', 1, 1, NULL, 'You did not confront the conflicting problem, but tried to create a Lose-Lose situation by compromising among the conflicting parties', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(611, 1, 2, 1, 'Two team members of your Scrum team Philip and Ramie was having a conflict. You used Forcing Conflict Resolution technique. Forcing is :', 1, 1, NULL, 'Forcing creates Win-Lose solution as the forcing person will be in winning situation & the person being forced will be in losing situation', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(612, 2, 5, 1, 'Two team members of your Scrum team Philip and Ramie was having a conflict. You used Forcing Conflict Resolution technique. Forcing is :', 1, 1, NULL, 'Forcing creates Win-Lose solution as the forcing person will be in winning situation & the person being forced will be in losing situation', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(613, 1, 2, 1, 'You have been given the responsibility of upgrading old server farm to the latest Quad Core Xeon Intel processors. The Up-gradation includes changing complete server hardware and may require restoring of data on these new servers. Two of your team members are having a conflict over a technical issue. What is the first thing you should do?', 1, 1, NULL, 'Always look at the problem that is causing the conflict, which is a technical issue in this case. So the very first thing you do is to meet the conflicting parties & try to understand the conflicting issue', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(614, 2, 5, 1, 'You have been given the responsibility of upgrading old server farm to the latest Quad Core Xeon Intel processors. The Up-gradation includes changing complete server hardware and may require restoring of data on these new servers. Two of your team members are having a conflict over a technical issue. What is the first thing you should do?', 1, 1, NULL, 'Always look at the problem that is causing the conflict, which is a technical issue in this case. So the very first thing you do is to meet the conflicting parties & try to understand the conflicting issue', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(615, 1, 2, 1, 'Philip and Ricky are having an argument over a technical issue in one of the Sprints. Philip tells Ricky that his views are not going to work, on listening this Ricky storms out of the room even though he knew his views about the problem were better than Philip\'s. Which type of conflict resolution is this?', 1, 1, NULL, 'Ricky is walking out of the conflict (potential conflict), hence he is withdrawing from the conflict', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(616, 2, 5, 1, 'Philip and Ricky are having an argument over a technical issue in one of the Sprints. Philip tells Ricky that his views are not going to work, on listening this Ricky storms out of the room even though he knew his views about the problem were better than Philip\'s. Which type of conflict resolution is this?', 1, 1, NULL, 'Ricky is walking out of the conflict (potential conflict), hence he is withdrawing from the conflict', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(617, 1, 2, 1, 'Philip and Ricky are having an argument over a technical issue in one of the Sprints. So they went to the Scrum Master to resolve the problem. He listens to both of them and conclude that both agree on certain things and they should concentrate on the grounds they agree. Which type of conflict resolution is this?', 1, 1, NULL, 'The conflicting parties agree on some of the points. They are not completely against the conflicting issues & are agreeing on the common grounds. This is Smoothing situation', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(618, 2, 5, 1, 'Philip and Ricky are having an argument over a technical issue in one of the Sprints. So they went to the Scrum Master to resolve the problem. He listens to both of them and conclude that both agree on certain things and they should concentrate on the grounds they agree. Which type of conflict resolution is this?', 1, 1, NULL, 'The conflicting parties agree on some of the points. They are not completely against the conflicting issues & are agreeing on the common grounds. This is Smoothing situation', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(619, 1, 2, 1, 'Philip and Ricky are having an argument over a technical issue in one of the Sprints. So they went to the Scrum Master to resolve the problem. He listens to both of them, however due to his busy schedule he says that he will listen to them in detail a week later. Which type of conflict resolution is this?', 1, 1, NULL, 'The Scrum Master is neither confronting the problem nor trying to find a resolution. He is withdrawing (procrastinating) from the conflicting situation', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(620, 2, 5, 1, 'Philip and Ricky are having an argument over a technical issue in one of the Sprints. So they went to the Scrum Master to resolve the problem. He listens to both of them, however due to his busy schedule he says that he will listen to them in detail a week later. Which type of conflict resolution is this?', 1, 1, NULL, 'The Scrum Master is neither confronting the problem nor trying to find a resolution. He is withdrawing (procrastinating) from the conflicting situation', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(621, 1, 2, 1, 'Russell is working as a Project Manager in KWSoft.com. He keeps a watch on each of his team member and reviews each document prepared by them. Which kind of manager is Russell?', 1, 1, NULL, 'In Theory X, the Manager micro-manages the project. He usually mistrusts the team members & reviews all the work', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(622, 2, 5, 1, 'Russell is working as a Project Manager in KWSoft.com. He keeps a watch on each of his team member and reviews each document prepared by them. Which kind of manager is Russell?', 1, 1, NULL, 'In Theory X, the Manager micro-manages the project. He usually mistrusts the team members & reviews all the work', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(623, 1, 2, 1, 'Russell is working as a Project Manager in KWSoft.com. He keeps faith on his team and occasionally reviews the documents prepared by his team members. Which kind of manager is Russell?', 1, 1, NULL, 'unlike in Theory-X, Theory-Y Managers completely trust the team members. They do not micro-manage & always manage by exception', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(624, 2, 5, 1, 'Russell is working as a Project Manager in KWSoft.com. He keeps faith on his team and occasionally reviews the documents prepared by his team members. Which kind of manager is Russell?', 1, 1, NULL, 'unlike in Theory-X, Theory-Y Managers completely trust the team members. They do not micro-manage & always manage by exception', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(625, 1, 2, 1, 'Ronaldo has just finished his project and has been assigned new project that needs working on a new technology which has never been used by the company before for any of the projects. He is currently executing the project and finds that he is slightly behind the schedule. Therefore, he announces INR 5,000 reward for any of the team member who would work overtime and help him to meet deadlines. Which type of power is he using?', 1, 1, NULL, 'By announcing INR 5,000 reward, Ronaldo is using the rewarding power. \n All other options do not use the reward option', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
