(1523, 1, 3, 1, 'After discussing with stakeholders, your team come up with the list of risks. Now you are plotting these risks as bubbles. Few other parameters are depicted on X and Y axis. Moreover, the bubble size also depicts parameter. Which technique are you using?', 1, 1, 'Simple', 'Hierarchical charts. Where risks have been categorized using more than two parameters, the probability and impact matrix cannot be used and other graphical representations are required. For example, a bubble chart displays three dimensions of data, where each risk is plotted as a disk (bubble), and the three parameters are represented by the x-axis value, the y-axis value, and the bubble size. An example bubble chart, with detectability and proximity plotted on the x and y axes, and impact value represented by bubble size.\n \n PMBOK Guide Sixth Edition (2018) PMI/PMI/11.3.2.6 DATA REPRESENTATION/p462', 0, 16, '1970-01-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL),
